00:45.100 --> 00:46.733
Just drive, man. Just go.

00:48.604 --> 00:51.438
What are you doing? Go fast.

00:57.379 --> 00:58.612
You okay?

00:58.614 --> 01:00.380
Just drive, man.

01:00.382 --> 01:02.716
Just drive.

01:10.693 --> 01:14.027
Dad, these expire today.

01:15.767 --> 01:17.331
It's fine, honey.

01:18.200 --> 01:19.599
Come on.

01:19.601 --> 01:21.268
I wouldn't feed you spoiled meat.

01:21.270 --> 01:24.838
Mom told me you used to cut mold
off food and eat around it.

01:24.840 --> 01:26.873
Well, maybe when I was a kid.

01:26.875 --> 01:28.709
And I turned out okay, didn't I?

01:31.480 --> 01:34.114
Kristen, the door!

01:40.122 --> 01:42.522
Afternoon, ma'am.

01:42.524 --> 01:43.990
We're looking for George Brown.

01:43.992 --> 01:45.892
I think you must have the wrong house.

01:45.894 --> 01:47.661
Nobody named George Brown lives here.

01:48.217 --> 01:49.730
George Brown?

01:50.427 --> 01:52.132
Are you addressing me?

01:52.134 --> 01:53.734
My name's James Grayson.

01:54.348 --> 01:56.036
Yeah, I'm sure you're right, Mr. Grayson.

01:56.038 --> 01:57.971
Mixups happen all the time.
Could I trouble you

01:57.973 --> 01:59.673
to come down to the local
police station with us

01:59.675 --> 02:01.074
so we can clear this up?

02:01.944 --> 02:03.977
I was barbecuing out back.

02:03.979 --> 02:06.680
- I mean, is this important?
- Actually, we have

02:06.682 --> 02:08.548
an arrest warrant for George Brown

02:08.550 --> 02:10.015
for a murder in Staten Island.

02:10.018 --> 02:13.019
Thing is, all the authorities
involved think he lives here.

02:13.021 --> 02:14.688
I think they think he's you.

02:14.690 --> 02:17.413
Pretty sure you're gonna want to
come with us and clear this up.

02:17.415 --> 02:19.092
Look, II don't know what's going on,

02:19.094 --> 02:20.327
but he's not George Brown.

02:20.329 --> 02:22.929
He's Jim Grayson. James Grayson.

02:22.931 --> 02:27.033
Ma'am, I'd like you
to lower your voice and back up.

02:28.804 --> 02:31.138
Mr. Grayson, you have a nice family here.

02:31.140 --> 02:33.106
You live in a nice neighborhood.

02:33.108 --> 02:35.876
Don't make me come back with
sirens and lights and...

02:35.878 --> 02:37.766
Let's just clear this up.

02:38.514 --> 02:40.013
Are you sure they know

02:40.015 --> 02:41.314
we're just here to file a motion?

02:41.316 --> 02:42.783
We've been sitting here over an hour.

02:42.785 --> 02:44.284
Yeah, I've spoken to everybody.

02:44.286 --> 02:45.983
They all know why we're here.

02:46.655 --> 02:48.855
The next arraignment is for George Brown.

02:48.857 --> 02:50.957
The defendant doesn't have
a lawyer. Mr. ColÃ³n.

02:51.655 --> 02:52.959
Would you be so kind

02:52.961 --> 02:55.095
as to stand in
for Mr. Brown's arraignment?

02:55.534 --> 02:58.565
I love the way they make it
sound like you have a choice.

02:58.567 --> 03:00.200
Yeah.

03:00.202 --> 03:02.569
I'd be, happy to, Your Honor.

03:03.792 --> 03:05.405
Okay...

03:05.407 --> 03:08.141
any family members here for George Brown?

03:08.143 --> 03:09.576
I'm his wife.

03:11.508 --> 03:14.147
I didn't know judges could
just assign lawyers like that.

03:14.149 --> 03:15.282
Are you our lawyer now?

03:15.284 --> 03:17.918
No. No, I'm just standing in

03:17.920 --> 03:20.454
until your husband gets his own attorney.

03:20.934 --> 03:22.422
We only have a few minutes

03:22.424 --> 03:23.890
to try to argue bail.

03:23.892 --> 03:25.125
Is your husband employed?

03:25.127 --> 03:26.430
If so, where?

03:26.432 --> 03:28.895
What's your family life
like? Does he have any friends?

03:28.897 --> 03:32.165
Yes. He owns a restaurant.

03:32.167 --> 03:34.468
He's a devoted father.
We have three kids.

03:34.470 --> 03:36.837
He's in a bowling league.
What else can I tell you?

03:36.839 --> 03:39.307
We just need to establish that
he has roots in the community.

03:39.309 --> 03:41.120
They want to make sure
he's not a flight risk.

03:41.122 --> 03:42.943
So, the police arrested your husband

03:42.945 --> 03:46.580
after looking for this murderer
for 18 years?

03:47.085 --> 03:48.882
Mrs. Grayson, it doesn't seem

03:48.884 --> 03:50.817
like the kind of thing
they would do baselessly.

03:50.819 --> 03:52.652
I don't know what to tell you.

03:52.654 --> 03:53.987
I haven't slept for two days.

03:53.989 --> 03:55.722
I just want my husband to come home.

03:55.724 --> 03:59.793
Look, my kids just want
their dad to come home.

04:07.836 --> 04:09.236
Are you my lawyer?

04:09.238 --> 04:12.305
For the purpose of this brief hearing.

04:12.307 --> 04:13.406
How bad is it?

04:13.408 --> 04:15.242
It's pretty bad.

04:15.244 --> 04:18.144
You're being charged with
a count of felony murder.

04:18.146 --> 04:21.447
You're looking at 25 years to life.

04:22.036 --> 04:24.117
But all I did was drive a car.

04:24.119 --> 04:26.820
Please state your name
for the court record.

04:36.468 --> 04:37.931
George Brown.

04:38.345 --> 04:39.866
How do you plead?

04:39.868 --> 04:42.769
Your Honor, we'd like to
enter a plea of not guilty.

04:42.771 --> 04:45.438
George Brown is a family man,
father of three,

04:45.440 --> 04:47.207
community volunteer,

04:47.209 --> 04:49.209
small business owner,

04:49.211 --> 04:51.599
and he employs seven
people in New Jersey.

04:51.601 --> 04:53.580
Your Honor, 18 years ago,

04:53.582 --> 04:54.981
George Brown was the getaway driver

04:54.983 --> 04:58.318
in a robbery at a Fast Cash
Express check cashing store.

04:58.320 --> 05:00.253
His coconspirator and older brother,

05:00.255 --> 05:03.089
Richard Brown, held up a 25yearold man

05:03.091 --> 05:05.425
by the name of Kirk Getty at gunpoint.

05:05.427 --> 05:07.460
He tied him up, gagged him,

05:07.462 --> 05:09.763
and Mr. Getty asphyxiated to death.

05:09.765 --> 05:14.100
The older Mr. Brown stole $8,000
and fled the scene of the crime.

05:14.798 --> 05:17.170
George Brown drove the getaway vehicle.

05:17.172 --> 05:19.606
Police arrested Richard, or Rick,

05:19.608 --> 05:21.608
a short while later.

05:21.610 --> 05:23.777
He was captured on tape calling George

05:23.779 --> 05:26.046
to tell him where
the stolen money was hidden

05:26.048 --> 05:28.348
and to take the money and flee.

05:28.350 --> 05:31.685
And apparently started a
new life as Jim Grayson.

05:31.687 --> 05:34.287
- Did you know he had a brother?
- No. No. No.

05:34.289 --> 05:36.890
George Brown has been
a fugitive from justice

05:36.892 --> 05:38.358
for 18 years, Your Honor.

05:38.864 --> 05:40.026
His fingerprints,

05:40.028 --> 05:41.728
lifted from the gun used in the robbery,

05:41.730 --> 05:42.929
were in the system

05:42.931 --> 05:45.198
and finally flagged in
New Jersey a few days ago.

05:45.704 --> 05:47.400
He's clearly a flight risk.

05:47.402 --> 05:49.302
And that is why we are
strenuously requesting

05:49.304 --> 05:52.105
that the Court deny Mr. Brown bail.

05:52.107 --> 05:53.940
So ordered.

05:53.942 --> 05:56.009
The defendant is remanded into custody.

06:04.598 --> 06:06.519
I'm so sorry.

06:06.521 --> 06:08.788
So, what happens now?

06:08.790 --> 06:11.925
Now you need to find
a good criminal lawyer,

06:11.927 --> 06:14.427
someone who knows their
way around felony murder.

06:14.429 --> 06:16.763
And where do we find one of those?

06:16.765 --> 06:19.833
When I get back to my office,
I'll email you a few names.

06:19.835 --> 06:22.502
And what about the two of you?

06:22.504 --> 06:25.305
Have you ever defended someone
charged with felony murder?

06:25.952 --> 06:26.873
Yes.

06:26.875 --> 06:28.775
And did you win?

06:28.777 --> 06:30.143
Yes.

06:30.145 --> 06:32.212
So why don't we start with you.

06:32.876 --> 06:35.415
After the fantastic job
we just did for you here?

06:35.921 --> 06:38.051
Apparently, he's been
making them look like fools

06:38.053 --> 06:39.319
for almost 20 years.

06:39.321 --> 06:41.988
I don't think Johnnie Cochran
could have gotten him off.

06:41.990 --> 06:43.456
We own a restaurant.

06:43.458 --> 06:45.291
We can pay you.

06:46.306 --> 06:47.427
Just meet with him.

06:47.429 --> 06:49.162
Listen to his side of the story.

06:49.164 --> 06:51.061
And then if it's not for you...

06:53.902 --> 06:55.602
I'll give him ten minutes.

06:55.604 --> 06:57.776
Thank you. Thank you so much.

07:00.008 --> 07:02.383
This is my boss, Dr. Jason Bull.

07:02.385 --> 07:04.577
Your wife wanted us to meet with you,

07:04.579 --> 07:07.147
hear your story, and see if we might

07:07.149 --> 07:08.662
want to be of help to you.

07:09.351 --> 07:10.956
How's she doing?

07:12.374 --> 07:14.287
About as well as can be expected

07:14.289 --> 07:16.389
given that after ten years of marriage,

07:16.391 --> 07:19.626
she just found out
she doesn't really know you.

07:20.257 --> 07:22.175
She doesn't know your real name.

07:22.931 --> 07:24.831
You want to tell us how you got here?

07:25.470 --> 07:27.500
It's not much of a story.

07:30.305 --> 07:32.739
I was 18 years old.

07:32.741 --> 07:34.474
My older brother had a DUI,

07:34.476 --> 07:36.710
so I was driving him home from work.

07:36.712 --> 07:38.278
He was a janitor.

07:38.280 --> 07:40.068
2:00 to 10:00 at the mall.

07:40.649 --> 07:43.450
He said he wanted to go
to this check cashing place.

07:43.452 --> 07:45.142
Did you go inside?

07:45.144 --> 07:48.021
I think I actually fell asleep
in the car waiting.

07:49.476 --> 07:53.478
I had no idea he was planning
on robbing the place.

07:53.595 --> 07:55.195
And what happened after that?

07:55.197 --> 07:58.131
Right after? A lot of nothing.

07:58.133 --> 08:00.533
Went about my life.
I went to school the next day.

08:00.535 --> 08:01.835
Came home. He wasn't there.

08:01.837 --> 08:03.258
Figured he was at work.

08:04.759 --> 08:07.807
But then I went to pick him up,
and he never came to the car.

08:07.809 --> 08:09.242
He was under arrest?

08:09.244 --> 08:10.410
Turns out he had gagged

08:10.412 --> 08:11.745
the guy behind the counter,

08:11.747 --> 08:13.880
but couldn't tie the gag
with his gloves on,

08:13.882 --> 08:15.161
so he took them off.

08:16.017 --> 08:18.685
Once they had his prints,
it was all over.

08:19.232 --> 08:20.987
And they picked him up at the mall.

08:20.989 --> 08:23.069
I, of course, knew none of this.

08:24.112 --> 08:26.326
Finally, Rick calls me
a couple days later from jail.

08:26.328 --> 08:28.995
Tells me where the money is.
Tells me to take it and run.

08:28.997 --> 08:32.030
So, if all you did was drive the car,

08:32.033 --> 08:34.234
and if you didn't even know
what your brother did

08:34.236 --> 08:36.936
when he was inside
the check cashing store,

08:36.938 --> 08:38.304
why did he tell you to run?

08:38.306 --> 08:39.905
Why didn't you go to the authorities,

08:39.908 --> 08:41.006
tell them your story?

08:41.630 --> 08:44.477
Rick told me the public defender told him

08:45.050 --> 08:47.313
they were about to put out
a warrant for my arrest.

08:47.315 --> 08:48.982
They were convinced
we were in it together.

08:48.984 --> 08:50.717
Something called a joint venture.

08:50.719 --> 08:52.652
In which case,

08:52.654 --> 08:55.421
even though you were
only the getaway driver,

08:55.423 --> 08:56.623
in the eyes of the law,

08:56.625 --> 08:58.525
you're as guilty as the
person who held the gun.

08:59.064 --> 09:02.962
And since someone died,
everyone's charged with murder.

09:04.633 --> 09:06.633
So now you're on the run.

09:08.203 --> 09:10.804
Moved around New England
for about a year.

09:10.806 --> 09:12.238
Slept in bus stations.

09:12.240 --> 09:13.787
Didn't talk to anyone.

09:15.163 --> 09:18.645
And then I met a guy
selling drugs in the bus station

09:18.647 --> 09:20.880
who told me he could get me

09:20.882 --> 09:24.551
a dead person's
Social Security number for $350.

09:26.354 --> 09:29.656
And Jim Grayson was born.

09:31.793 --> 09:33.431
Stupid.

09:33.929 --> 09:35.795
I went to renew my liquor license

09:35.797 --> 09:37.330
about a month ago.

09:37.332 --> 09:38.865
They asked for my prints.

09:38.867 --> 09:40.647
I didn't think a thing about it.

09:42.148 --> 09:44.317
Pretty sure that's what did me in.

09:48.276 --> 09:50.210
Mrs. Grayson?

09:51.112 --> 09:53.079
So, that was an awfully long ten minutes.

09:53.081 --> 09:54.147
How's he doing?

09:55.817 --> 09:57.183
That's funny.

09:57.185 --> 09:59.719
He asked the exact same
question about you.

09:59.721 --> 10:01.721
My sense is that he is overcome

10:01.723 --> 10:05.058
with regret and remorse,

10:05.060 --> 10:08.795
and at the exact same time,
he is angry and bitter

10:08.797 --> 10:11.364
because any logical
examination of the facts

10:11.366 --> 10:12.637
suggests that...

10:13.435 --> 10:15.140
he didn't really do anything.

10:15.503 --> 10:17.170
You sound like you're on his side.

10:17.172 --> 10:19.272
You sound like you believe him.

10:20.976 --> 10:22.609
I guess I do.

10:23.189 --> 10:25.879
Does that mean you'd be willing
to represent him?

10:28.216 --> 10:30.416
I guess it does.

10:42.360 --> 10:44.305
ADA Peluso. Thanks for coming by.

10:44.330 --> 10:45.562
Dr. Bull's expecting you.

10:45.564 --> 10:47.881
Any excuse to get out of the office.

10:48.420 --> 10:51.668
So, I'm guessing we're all here
to talk plea deal?

10:51.670 --> 10:53.103
Well, I can't speak for you,

10:53.105 --> 10:56.607
but Dr. Bull and I are here
to talk about dismissal.

10:56.609 --> 10:59.476
Dismissal?
Well, it's good to have a dream.

11:00.646 --> 11:02.613
Well, the joke's not lost on me,

11:02.615 --> 11:05.382
but let's talk it through for a second.

11:05.384 --> 11:07.151
No matter how you slice it,

11:07.153 --> 11:10.554
prosecuting that man
is still a moral conundrum.

11:11.029 --> 11:14.333
After all, the primary function
of our criminal justice system

11:14.335 --> 11:17.995
is to provide deterrence,
protect society,

11:17.997 --> 11:20.030
punish people who commit crimes,

11:20.032 --> 11:23.467
and rehabilitate criminals
once we have them in custody.

11:23.469 --> 11:25.435
Now, hasn't all of that

11:25.437 --> 11:27.771
already been accomplished
with regard to George Brown?

11:27.773 --> 11:29.640
He's led a successful and productive life

11:29.642 --> 11:30.941
since the robbery.

11:30.943 --> 11:32.843
He's not a danger to society.

11:32.845 --> 11:36.079
And he has no intention
to commit another crime.

11:36.081 --> 11:37.815
So...

11:37.817 --> 11:41.084
what would be the point
of sending him to prison?

11:41.935 --> 11:44.888
Dr. Bull, this trial isn't
an ethics symposium.

11:44.890 --> 11:47.591
We can't just give someone
a â€œget out of jail freeâ€ card

11:47.593 --> 11:49.426
for evading the law.

11:49.428 --> 11:50.828
Come on, did you really think

11:50.830 --> 11:52.763
I was gonna roll over
for you that easily?

11:52.765 --> 11:54.231
He's an innocent man.

11:54.233 --> 11:55.532
Maybe he is...

11:56.101 --> 11:57.826
and maybe he isn't.

11:58.571 --> 12:00.870
That is why we're having a trial.

12:03.039 --> 12:04.575
See you on the ice, gentlemen.

12:06.045 --> 12:07.644
A man can't be found guilty

12:07.646 --> 12:10.614
of a murder simply because
it happened in his midst.

12:10.616 --> 12:13.317
And he absolutely can't be found guilty

12:13.319 --> 12:14.818
of a murder in which he took no part

12:14.820 --> 12:16.220
and was not even aware.

12:16.222 --> 12:17.747
So that's our narrative?

12:17.749 --> 12:19.022
We're gonna make the government prove

12:19.024 --> 12:20.958
that George knew what was going on?

12:20.960 --> 12:23.293
Yeah. To be held accountable
for a joint venture,

12:23.295 --> 12:25.028
George had to have known

12:25.030 --> 12:27.798
that his brother was gonna
commit armed robbery.

12:27.800 --> 12:29.266
And he didn't know.

12:29.268 --> 12:31.301
How in the world are we gonna prove that?

12:31.303 --> 12:34.137
We'll start by showing the jury
what kind of man he is.

12:34.139 --> 12:36.641
And the key to that is his wife.

12:36.643 --> 12:37.674
Chunk.

12:37.676 --> 12:39.142
Let's get her in here.

12:39.144 --> 12:41.879
What's important is when she
is sitting in that courtroom,

12:41.881 --> 12:44.681
that she sends the right message
to the jurors.

12:44.683 --> 12:46.316
She loves this man.

12:46.318 --> 12:48.685
She trusts this man.

12:49.085 --> 12:50.254
This is a good man.

12:50.256 --> 12:52.689
All right. I'll do whatever I can

12:52.691 --> 12:54.625
to get her in here today.

12:54.627 --> 12:56.960
And what do we know about how
and from whom

12:56.962 --> 12:59.162
he bought this fake
Social Security number?

12:59.164 --> 13:01.498
Well, he says he met a guy
at a bus station.

13:01.500 --> 13:02.833
Says his name was Joe,

13:02.835 --> 13:04.935
and he sold cell phones in Burlington,

13:04.937 --> 13:06.270
which makes sense,

13:06.272 --> 13:08.438
'cause to buy a cell phone,
you have to buy a plan;

13:08.440 --> 13:10.594
To buy a plan,
you have to give the merchant

13:10.596 --> 13:12.181
your Social Security number.

13:12.183 --> 13:13.891
Well, at least you did back then.

13:13.916 --> 13:15.715
Any thoughts on voir dire?

13:15.717 --> 13:17.751
The more I think about it,
the more I think

13:17.753 --> 13:21.254
the answer lies in... generativity.

13:21.256 --> 13:22.956
Okay, I'm out.

13:22.958 --> 13:24.524
Yeah, me, too.

13:24.526 --> 13:25.959
Seven years of college

13:25.961 --> 13:28.228
and I have no idea
what you're talking about.

13:28.230 --> 13:31.264
Generativity is the concern for,

13:31.266 --> 13:33.533
and belief in, the future.

13:33.535 --> 13:35.435
And a commitment
to the idea that no matter

13:35.437 --> 13:39.139
how bad things may be
at any given moment,

13:39.141 --> 13:42.309
you can persevere and redeem yourself.

13:43.612 --> 13:45.545
Let me give you an example.

13:45.547 --> 13:46.913
Marissa.

13:47.769 --> 13:49.616
If you say so.

13:49.618 --> 13:51.117
I mean it as a compliment.

13:51.119 --> 13:53.520
It's an admirable quality in a person.

13:53.522 --> 13:56.323
So, tell me your life story.

13:56.325 --> 13:58.592
Boil it down to what
you think's relevant.

13:58.594 --> 14:02.896
I was adopted into a wonderful family.

14:03.243 --> 14:04.864
And meeting my birth parents

14:04.866 --> 14:06.499
made me appreciate different ways

14:06.501 --> 14:08.568
my life could have ended up.

14:09.437 --> 14:11.125
But I like the way it's gone.

14:11.873 --> 14:14.174
I worked for Homeland Security.

14:14.176 --> 14:17.177
I developed an algorithm to try
to help understand people,

14:17.179 --> 14:19.300
which led me to you.

14:20.349 --> 14:23.894
I have had a string
of interesting relationships.

14:23.896 --> 14:27.392
Some good, one Kyle.

14:28.935 --> 14:31.291
But none of them broke me,

14:31.293 --> 14:33.606
and none of them made me who I am.

14:36.365 --> 14:37.797
You see?

14:37.799 --> 14:39.599
Highly generative people,

14:39.601 --> 14:41.468
they're driven to help others

14:41.470 --> 14:42.869
for the betterment of the future,

14:42.871 --> 14:45.005
because they see the arcs of their lives

14:45.007 --> 14:47.307
as redemption stories.

14:47.309 --> 14:48.875
And that's what we want.

14:48.877 --> 14:52.212
